  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In a letter to the editor of the Standard, there is this explanation regarding William Lloyd Garrison&apos;s letter to Mr. Charles Hazeltine, Feb. 9, 1873: &quot;In view of the approaching dissolution of the late Enoch Hazeltine, Mr. Garrison was invited to conduct the funeral services of his life-time colaborer. Prevented by precarious health, he offered to send a letter containing the substance of what he would say if present. The letter was unavoidably delayed too late for its special purpose, and the following tribute was sent.&quot; Garrison pays tribute to Enoch Hazeltine&apos;s life: &quot;Hence his prompt and zealous espousal of all the marked reformatory movements of the present century--not at the eleventh hour, but among the earliest in the field; never waiting for reenforcements, or for that partial success which seems to be prophetic of ultimate triumph, but standing alone if need be, never doubting how the conflict would end.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Printed in this clipping, there is also a letter by Wendell Phillips to Charles Hazeltine, Feb. 9, 1873, sending his condolences on the death of Enoch Hazeltine. Phillips writes about Enoch Hazeltine: &quot;I remember your father&apos;s name as often on the lips of those early laborers, though I seldom, if ever, enjoyed his society more than a few minutes at a convention. These are precious memories. ...&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
